{"/service/ndnp/cohi/batch_cohi_jasper_ver01/data/sn86063397/00340586177/1921012701/0153.xml":{"full_text":"THE ELK MOUNTAIN PILOT\nVOLUME XXXXV.\nLocal and Personal\nRoger Nelson arrived home on Sun\nday\u2019s train.\n\u2014o\nMrs. M. J. Boyle came in on last\nThursday\u2019s train.\nA. L. Mi ls returned home from\nGunnison Wednesday.\nFrank Buster is in town from over\non the Perry Bros, ranch.\nP. G. Elder returned home from a\nshort business trip to Denver\nWednesday.\nThe Bulkley mine is to resume ope\nrations again this week after a cou\nple of weeks id'eness.\nJohn McGosker arrived home\nWednesday. He has been spending\nsome time in Gunnison.\nMike Fisher made a business trip\ndown to the Eccher section\nWednesday of last week.\nJos. Faussone went to Glacier\nThursday to serve some papers on a\nman by tho name of Frock.\n\u2014HJ\u2014\nCha a Henderson, an employee at\nthe Bulkley m\u2019ne for several months,\nleft for Denver Wednesday.\nW. H. Whalen returned heme from\nDenver Sunday where he attended\nthe Good Roads convention.\nMrs. John Heuchemer went tover to\nSargent Thursday for a short visit\nwith her daughter, Mrs. Ruie Watters.\nMr. W. F. Bragg, Sociological work\ner for the C. F. I. company came in\nlast Thursday, remaining several\ndays.\nMrs. W. S. Bailey and children\nspent several days of last week in\ntown as guests at the Thos. McNeil\nhome.\nGeo. Spehar took his little daugh\nter to Gunnison Wednesday tp have\na bad tooth out. They returned home\nThursday.\nFOR TRADE OR SALE: Alfalfa\nsand. Water right unexcelled. What\nhave you to offer? J. TAYLOR, Jr.\n3-5 t Florence, Colo.\nThe Ladies\u2019 Aid members were de\nlightfully entertained by. Mrs. Adams\nand Mrs. Benscn at the home of the\nlatter on Thursday afternoon, Jan. 20.\nJohn and Martin Conforti came\ndown from Smith Hill Sunday and\nleft Monday for Boulder, where they\nw.ill spend the remainder of the win\nter.\nMr. Angelo Welch, who was so bad\nly injured on the railroad near Smith\nbreaker last week, and taken over to\nSalida hospital, is getting along\nnicely.\nThe force was cut at Bmith Hill\nlast week and the mine is not work\ning the early part of this week, on\naccount of repairs being made at the\nbreaker.\nMartin Trainer, who had his leg\nbroken just above the ankle, in an\naccident at the C. F. I. mine Thurs\nday, was. taken over to Minnequa hos\npital Friday.\nA number of the men were down\nfrom Smith Hill Sunday, Monday and\nTuesday. They returned to the Hill\nTuesday evening to be ready for work\nWednesday morning.\nMrs. Edith' Wilson who has been\ncooking for Mrs. Haymaker at Smith\nHill for some time, departed Thurs\nday for Denver, having resigned her\nposition at the Hill.\nThe hams and cigars were distrib\nuted to the C. F. I. employees Sat\nurday evening after which a free\ndance was given at the City Hall, a\nlarge crowd attending and a good\ntime reported by all.\nA letter received from Jackson\nMooney states that they are now lo\ncated at 104 Dudley Ave-, Venice,\nCalifornia, and wishes the Pilot to be\nsent to that address. He says there\nis some difference in Crested Butte\nand Venice climate.\nGet busy. Keep busy. Is your job\nunsafe? Is it permanent? You want\na life long business. You can get In\nto a business selling more than 137\nWatkins Products direct to farmers\nif you own auto or team or can get\none; if you can give bond with per\nsonal sureties. We back you with big\nselling helps. 62 years in business,\n20,000,000 users of our products.\nWrite for Information wehre you can\nget territory. J. R. Watkins Co., De\npartment C, Winona, Minnesota.\nA Weekly Newspaper of Interest to the Elk Mountain Region\nA large and interested crowd at\nended the Educational meeting\nwhich was held at the U. C. church\nlast Sunday afternoon. Mr. W. E.\nBragg, Sociological worker of the C.\nF. 1., was the principal speaker.\nFriends of the R. H. Mace family\nwill be sorry tc hear that their son\nFrank is in a local hospital at Mis\nsoula, suffering from a se\nvere attack of rheumatism and heart\ntrouble.\nA banquet was given to the com\nmittees and other C. F. I. employ\nees here at the Elk Mountain Hotel\nFriday evening by Mr. D. A. Stout of\nPueblo.\nL. came in from Gunni-;\nson Thursday to install a phene for\nA. P. McCarver.\nMr. and Mrs. Tony Tezak, Jr, the\nnewly weds, arrived home Thursday\nfrom Leadville.\nMiss Mary Nemanic came home\nfrom Gunnison Friday.\nOne Time Citizen Gone\nNews reached here Tuesday evening\nof the death of Mr. Tim TinsJey at\nhis home in Glenwood Springs on\nTuesday at 1 p. m. He had been ill\nfor several months and the end had\nbeen expected for some time. Mr.\nTins\u2019ey was 70 years of age last De\ncembe Three children, Mrs. P. .T.\nMorgan, Miss Martha, and Harold\nBreen reside in Crested Butte, and\nleft Wednesday to attend the funeral.\nBesides these, Mr. Tinsley leaves a\nwife, two daughters and, two sons,\nall of whom reside in Glenwood, to\nmourn his death.\nHe was for a number of years a\nresident of Crested Butte and Flor\nesta, being in the employ of the C.\nF. I. company. Always a well liked\nand respected citizen. Mr. Tinsley\nhad a host of friends in this vicinity\nwho will read of his death with sor\nrow.\nTHE BORDERLAND\n\u201cThere is a mystic borderland that\nlies\nJust past the limits of our w>crk-day\nworld.\nAnd it is peopled with the friends\nwe met\nAnd loved a year, a month, a week,\nor day.\nAnd parted from with aching hearts,\nyet knew\nThat through the distance we must\nloose the hold\nOf hand with hand, and only clasp\nthe thread\nOf Memory. But still so close we\nfeel this land,\nSo sure we are that these same\nhearts are true,\nThat when in waking dreams there\ncomes a call\nThat sets the thread of memory\naglow.\nWe know that just by stretching out\nthe hand\nIn written word or love or book or\nflower,\nThe waiting hand will clasp our own\nonce more\nAcross the silence, in the same, old\nway.\u201d\n\u2014Author Unknown.\nTODAY\nToday is what you have. It is also\nwhat you are. And, again. Today is\nwhat you do. And if you haven\u2019t\nanything, and aren\u2019t anybody, and do\nnothing\u2014why, then, for you there is\nno Today.\nFor Today is music. Today is art.\nToday is literature. Today is joy.\nToday is wverk. Today is play. To\nday is life.\nYesterday is no problem\u2014for it is\npast. Tomorrow is no problem\u2014for\nit isn\u2019t here. Today is supremacy.\nToday is opportunity!\nCrowd in upon it, then. Today\u2014\ntake hold upon its faintest chance.\nSpread your smiles\u2014Today. Be game\n\u2014Today. Be glad and grea t. \u2014Today.\nToday, the day, is your day.\nToday is time and change doing its\njob. Are you a vital part of the play?\nToday you may start out all anew.\nToday you may put to use what you\nlearned a day ago. The center of\nyour entire life may revQlve about\nToday.\nBut, above all things, do not fear\nToday. Let all worry slide. All\nthings that do not count\u2014let them\ngo, too. Work and help and love\nToday.\nFor this Today will never dawn\nagain!\u2014George Adams.\nMaking. an Impression\nWe do the kind of printing that\nmakes a favorable Impression wher\never it is seen. We put intelligence\nInto our work, and use artistic judg\nment in display, choices of Inks and\npaper. You will like the extra touch\nof excellence we give to your work.\nTry us. Elk Mountain Pilot.\nThe Pilot gives you all the news.\nCRESTED BUTTE, COLORADO, THURSDAY, JANUARY 27, 1921\nSOMEBODY POISONED MY DOG\nSomebody poisoned my deg today,\nThough he never did an one ill;\nAnd so he is through with ihs canine\nplay\nAnd his waggelty tail is still.\nNo more shall I walk in the fields\nwith him\nAlong at my side to jog,\nAnd \u2014I don\u2019t care if my eyes are dim,\nSomebody poisoned my dog!\nHe was homely, I know, as a dog\ncould be,\nAmi only a mongrel, too;\nBut I loved him and he loved me\nAs people and degs may do.\nNothing on earth cou\u2019d disturb his\ntrust\nOr his love and his faith befog.\nAnd now he lies here in the snow\nSomebody poisoned my dog!\nHe crawled to my feet ami he licked\nmy hand.\nAnd then with a gasp he died;\nAnd\u2014though some people can\u2019t un\nderstand\nI patted his head\u2014and cried!\nFor it isn\u2019t funny to here a friend\nFrom off this \u201cearthly cog,\u201d\nAnd he was loyal unto the end\nScmebody poisoned my dog!\nI wonder how any one could have\ndone\nThis poor little fellow harm;\nBut here he lies his race is run\nThough bis body\u2019s stilf soft and\nwarm.\nMy life Is lived on a peaceful plan,\nMy pace is a quiet job.\nBut\u2014l wish I could find the snake of\na man\nWho poisoned my little dog.\nAuthor unknown.\nAbove poem, handed us by a friend,\nis very appropriate at this time,\nwhen some \u201csrmke of a man\u201d is out\npoisuning all the dogs around. Sev\neral vauab\u2019e ones are among those\npoisoned lately and if the \u201csnake\u201d\nwere caught red-handed we wiould\nhate to vouch for his safety.\nEDUCATIONAL MEETING\nThe past week seems to have been\nan educational week', as several meet\nings on that topic were held, the\nmost important of whicK was at the\nU. C. church at four p. m. Sunday,\nabout forty-five attending.\nMr. W. E. Bragg spoke on the Ed\nucational problems of today, includ\ning the betterment and uplifting of\nour schoo\u2019s, Sunday schools, etc.\nMiss Bertha Boyd, teacher of the\nprimary grade gave a very interest\ning talk, as did Mrfe. M. A. Jaynes.\nOther speakers were Dr. A. Taylor,\nMr. and Mrs .W. A. Boyd, Mrs. L. G.\nEspey, Mrs. W. E. NasK Mr. E. G.\nGladstone and others.\nA Red ami Blue contest was then\norganized and a captain chosen for\neach side. The side which succeeds\nin geting the largest attendance out\nto Sunday school at the end of a cer\ntain period, being the winner. Most\nall who were present promised to at\ntend Sunday school.\nRecreation and Educational Commit\ntee Visits School\nMr. W. E.-Bragg of the Sociological\ndepartment of the C. F. I. com\npany, visited school Friday. On Mon\nday he again visited school Accompa\nnied by the local committee on Rec\nreation and Education, which consists\nof Messrs. W. EL Nash, Thos. McNeil,\nRaphael Giardino, and Tony Kochevar.\nMr. Bragg spoke to the seventh and\ne ghth grades, a\u2019so the h gh school.\nHe said that the country would be\nwhat the children of today made It\nin later years. He had a few exam\nples to show them what the value of\nan education is to them. He said\nthat if one did not get a good educa\ntion he could not hold a good posi\ntion; that if one cou\u2019d not fill the po\nsition he had, he could not advance\nto a better one. He urged all to go\nas far In school as they possibly\ncould.\nExplaining Crooked Road.\nFor the benefit of automlblllsts who\nhave wondered why the road from Exe\nter to Hampton, N. H., Is so crooked. It\nla explained that when the first settle\nments were being made In New Hamp\nshire, a bear made a night raid on that\npart of the Hampton settlement known\nas Wigwam row, and men In pursuit\nthe next morning followed its tracks\nIn the light snow to its watering place\nat Squamscott falls, and built the road\naccordingly.\u2014Boston Herald.\nOf Course.\n\"The club members seem to have a\ngreat deal to growl about\u201d\n\u201cWell, ain\u2019t It the duty of an effi\ncient steward to provide that?\u201d \u2014Lou-\nisville Courier-Journal.\ntubsoribe for Tho Pilot.\n20 YEARS AGO\nCopied from the Files of the Elk\nMountain Pilot\nJanuary 29, 1901.\nMrs. Geo. Walters was visiting in\nGunnison Friday.\nGeK>. Adams was up from Gunnison\nWednesday on a business trip.\nW. A-. Welch returned Saturday\nfrom a business trip to Pueblo.\nTony Stanica was badly injured in\nthe mine on Wednesday last by a fall\nof coal.\nG. H. Judd arrived from Vulcan\nWednesday and went over to Gothic\nto remain for a while.\nMr. Fred Jarvis was married to\nMiss Winnifred Irene Ottaway at Al\namosa on Monday. They will reside\nal Salida.\nMrs. Jos. Runnoe entertained a\nnumber of friends at dinner Saturday\nafternoon. (The Runnoes now live\non a ranch near Austin, Colo.)\nThe Mutual Life Insurance com\npany of New York, through its local\nrepresentative, V. E. Metzler, has\npaid the heirs of Mrs. Esther Chap\npell SI,OOO insurance.\nRalph Neesham came in Sunday\nfrom Sunshine, near Glenwood, where\nhe has been for the past couple of\nmonths. (Ralph, with his family, re\nsideq at Somerset and pays C. B. a\nvisit each summer.)\nMiss May Young has purchased the\nSchaefer stock of tobaccos and con\nfectionary and will conduct the busi\nness as formerly. (Miss Young\u2019s\nmother, Mrs. R. A. Young, now runs\na millinery and notion store at the\nsame place, Miss May having passed\non several years ago.)\nGeo. L. Miller has commenced the\nconstruction of a 26x60 store build\ning to be located directly across the\nstreet from the K. of P. building.\n(This 'buildingi, now owned by C. J.\nDiel? is now used as a skating rink,\nMrs. Susie Miller using the rear part\nas undertaking rooms.\nMiss Maude Bray was pleasantly\nsurprised last Tuesday evening by a\n\u2019arge party of. friends calling unex\npectedly at her home to spend the\nevening. Dancing and music were\nthe features of the evening, a delic\nious lunch then being served. Miss\nBray proved a charming hostess.\nSCHOOL COLUMN\nDave Vernon was a visitor at\nschool Monday.\nJoseph Villotti entered the ninth\ngrade Monday morning.\nVisit school, get acquainted with\nthe teacher and see how your girl or\nbey Is progressing.\nMrs. Geo. Andreatta visited in\nMisses Boyd\u2019s and Eastman\u2019s rooms\nTuesday afternoon.\nReport is we are to have a couple\nmore high school pupils in the near\nfuture. We hope so. The more the\nmerrie*.\nThe Misses Bertha Boyd and Nelle\nEastman were out-going passengers\non Friday\u2019s train to Gunnison. They\nreturned Sunday.\nEvre hear the seng, \u201cWhy Don\u2019t\nParents Visit the Schools?\u201d Be a\ngood idea for the children to learn it\nand sing it at home.\nThe Future of New York City\nA man who had always lived in the\ncountry visited New York City for\nthe first time. He was amazed at the\nsights and gazed about in open\nmouthed wonder, to the amusement\nof of his city-bred friend.\n\u2018\u2018This is nothing,\u201d said the city\nman, \u201ccome back five years from now\nand see how we have advanced.\u201d The\ncountry man promised to do so.\nWhen he went home he told his wife\nof his intended visit five years hence\nand for a time he could talk of noth\ne\u2019se. Then one morning he announced\nthat he had given up the trip. When\nasked the reason he replied:\n\u201cI dreamed last night that the five\nyears were up and I was in New York\nCity. I stood at the intersection of\ntwo streets and looked about me.\nAn automobile came rushing at me\nfrom one direction; a motorcycle\nfrom another. An auto truck was\ncoming from behind and a taxicab\nspeedily approaching. I looked up\nand saw overhead a runaway airship,\nrapidly descending. In desperation I\nlooked down. I was standing on a\nmanhole cover. It was my only\nchance. I lifted the cover and jumped\ninto the hole just in time to be run\nover by a subway train.\u2019*\nCurrent Comment\nMy Waller Thomas Mills.\nPRESIDENT OF THE SCHOOL OF SOCIAL SERVICE\nOSRKELEV, CALIFORNIA\nTHE GAMBLER\u2019S STRANGLE GRIP\nIn this modern world each useful\nperson renders at least some single\nservice or produces some single com\nmodity. which he can exchange in the\nmarket for all of the things and ser\nvices he needs for his own and for\nhis family\u2019s use. As a producer he\nmay produce but a single thing, but\nas a consumer he uses many things.\nEach one produces for the many in\nturn, each producing a single com\nmodity, provide the many things for\neach consumer.\n\nEach useful person is able to buy\nout of the market because he puts\nsomething into it. When he lets go\nof the one thing he produces, he\nmust obtain for It some sort of\nthing which in turn wilL be receiv\nable in the markets in exchange for\nall his supplies. Money is just such a\nsomething. It is nothing other than\nan order for goods which can be\ntransferred without indorsement and\nis universally acceptab'e. A bank\ncheck is such an order, with the\nexception, however, that it is trans\nferable only by Indorsement.\n\nMoney or its equivalent should be\nalways obtainable in consideration\nof goods or services already delivered.\nIn such a case it is a cash transac\ntion. Credits should be obtainable\nonly In consideration of goods or\nservices already in storage, or in\nprocess of production, or within the\ncertain reach and ability of the bor\nrower to produce.\nm\nIt is the business of a bank to\ndeal in credits. Interest is a pay\nment for the use of credits. Under\nour present banking system the\nFederal Reserve Board has the pow\ner greatly to deflate these credits,\nthat is, greatly to increase or great\nly to decrease the volume of credits\navailable for the transaction of bu i\nness.\nAn increase in credits leads to an\nincrease in price-. A decrease in\ncredits leads to a decrease in prices.\nIf debts are mada when prices are\nhigh, the burden of debt is greatly\nincreased when prices fall. If debts\nare made when prices are low, the\nburden of debt greatly decreases as\nprices rise. EVERY INCREASE OR\nDECREASE *IN* THE GENERAL\nAVERAGE OF PfcICES, AND\nHENCE EVERY INCREASE OR DE\nCREASE IN AVAILABLE CREDITS,\nMEANS AN INJURY TO SOME\nONE.\n\nIt is a crime that Has been re\npeatedly committed, it is an out\nrage now definitely provided for\nunder our laws, that the manipula\ntion of prices thru constant shifting\nin the volume of credits can con\ntinuously involve productive work\ners in great liabilities assumed\nwhen prices are h gh and then force\nthem into certain ruin as prices\nfall.\nIt was in the midst of a s tuation\nof this sort that the Populist party\ndemanded the establishment of\nnational warehouses and the grant\ning to producers of ample credits\nto be secured on their warehouse\nreceipts. That would have made\npossible exchanges directly between\nthe producers and it would have\nplaced forever the means of pay\nment and the volume and control\nof credit in the hands of the useful\npeople.\n\nThe Popu'ists were abused, mis\nrepresented, laughed at and finally\nbetrayed, but what the Populists\npropro ed for tha producers, the\nFederal Reserve Board provides for\nthe gamblers, with the provision that\nwarehouse receipts can be made the\nbasis of credits only after tha own\nership of the products has passed\nfrom the hands of the farmers.\nOnly a little while ago the Press\nwas filled with declarations that the\nonly way to a return of prosperity\nwas thru increased F r \u00b0d uc^\u2019on Pro\nduction was increased. The gran\naries are full. The warehouses are\nbulging with untaken goods, and\nsome four or five million of produc\ntive wicrkers are out of employment.\nThey are beginning to beg for bread-\nThey are forming in breadlines. ALL\nTHIS BECAUSE IT WAS DECiDED\nBY THE GAMBLERS THAT IT IS\nNUMBER 7\nNOW TIME TO \u201cDEFLAIE\u201d, THAT\nIS. TO DECREASE CREDIT.\nThe State of North Dakota estab\nlished a state owned bank. It has\nrendered services of the greatest Im\nportance in these hours of stress.\nThe gamblers however, plotted its\nruin. It was proposed in the law\nwhich created this bank that pro\nducers should obtain credit on ware\nhouse receipts issued on their pro\nducts while still in the ownership of\nthe producers. The effort to destroy\nthe bank fias reacted on those who\nwould destroy it. The bank has be\ncome the center of a people\u2019s hope.\nIn South Dakota the gamblers have\nmade a most modest proposal. They,\ntoo, propose a state owned bank; that\nthe state shall furnish the capital\u2014\neight millions; that the bankers shall\nfurnish \u2019two millions and the bankers\nwho provide the two millions are to\nhave 'the management of the whole\nten millions.\nThe Bank of North Dakota is an\nswerable to and is controlled by an\nIndustrial Commission composed of\nelected officials and subject to recall.\nThe Bank of North Dakota was capi\ntalized by an issue of two million\nin state bonds. The gamblers com\nbined to prevent the sale of these\nbonds. But now the same gamblers\npropose the sa\u2019e of e\u2019ght million in\nstate bonds in South Dakota, but\nThe ruin which is overtaking busi\nthis central credit agency is to be so\nestablished that this capital so fur\nnished is to be managed, not by au\nthorities answerable to the people,\nbut by gamblers answerable to one\nanother.\nne-s is for lack of a market. The lack\nof a market for any one article is be\ncause of the inability of someone to\nsell some other article. Those who\nare to be consumers ought first to be\nproducers. Those who are to be buy\ners must first be sellers. The denial\nof credit is strangling the market.\nThe denial of c.dit has set prices\ntumbling. It has brought foreclos\nure; attachments are enforced sales\nin a broken market. The resources\nand powers of no state are sufficient\nto deal effectively with this situation.\nThe trouble is that the markets are\nnational. The Constitution of the\nUnited States gives to the National\nGovernment a practical monopoly in\nfinancial affairs. Congress alone can\nact effectively, and the gamblers who\nhave promoted this denial of credit\nam! are p o ee:ling with plans to ap\npropriate the p\u2019edged collaterals of\na nation, are in control of*C~ngress.\nThe wheels could be started imme\ndiately. Unemployment could be\nmade an end of. The condition of in\ndustrial paralysis and of commercial\nstagnation could he ended at once, by\nex.luding all gamblers from the mar\nket, by f rbidding anyone to buy\nwhat he oes not use; making it a\nfelony to grant credit gambling\npurpose-; ruling the speculator out\nof the market; granting the reeded\ncredits to the real produ\u00abe\u201cs; giving\nthem a chr nee to exchange the r pro\nducts wi h *cne another; and by re\n.s\u2019oring credits r store prices; and by\nrestoiing p ices make the sa\u2019e of\npzoducts possible on a bisis which\nwou\u2019d not mean the ru n of the pro\nducers.\nWill Congress do it? Either this\nCongress or the Congress recently\ne'ected will d> it cr another election\nwill create a Congress that will rep\nresent the useful people and not the\ngamblers.\n$100 Reward, $100\nThe readers of this paper will be\npleased to learn that there la at leaat\none dreaded disease that science baa\nbeen able to cure In all Ita stages and\nthat Is catarrh. Catarrh being greatly\nInfluenced by consUtutional conditions\nrequires constitutional treatment. Hall\u2019s\nCatarrh Medicine le taken Internally and\nacta thru the Blood on the Mucous Sur\nfaces of the System thereby destroying\nthe foundation of the disease, giving the\npatient strength by building up the con\nstitution and assisting nature In doing Ita\nwork. The proprietors have so much\nfaith In the curative power of Hall's\nCatarrh Medicine that they offer One\nHundred Dollars for any case that It falls\nto cure. Send for list of testimonials.\nAddress F. J. CHENEY St CO., Toledo.\nOhio. Sold by all Druggists, 76c.\nFARM WANTED\nWanted to hear from owner of\nfarm or goed \u2019and for sale worth the\nprice naked. L. C. Jones, Box 551,\nOlnev, Illinois.\nBill heads, letter heads, envelopes,\ncards, etc., printed at the Pilot office.","height":"19792","width":"14740"}}
